, Essex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1290–":"1290–Deceased","1290–Male":"1290–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1314–Male":"1314–Deceased","1265–Male":"1265–Deceased","1265–Female":"1265–Deceased","1314":"1314","1265":"1265","1290":"1290","Theydon Garnon, Essex, England":"Theydon Garnon, Essex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Boice","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Boyce  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Boyce","meanings":["English and Irish (mainly Donegal): of Norman origin, a habitational name from from one or more places in Normandy named with Old French <i>bois</i> ‘wood, grove’, especially Bois-Arnault and Bus-Saint-Rémy (Eure), and Bosc-le-Hard (Seine-Maritime), each of which is known to have given its name to an aristocratic Norman family in England. The name was taken by the Normans from England to Ireland, where it was also adopted to Anglicize Irish <b>Ó Buadhaigh</b> (see   Bogue  ).","English: variant of   Bush  , influenced by Old French <i>bois</i> in 1 above, or else a translation of this term.","Americanized form of French   Bois  ."]}]},{"name":"Brian","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Irish origin: perhaps from an Old Celtic word meaning ‘high’ or ‘noble’. The name has been perennially popular in Ireland, in particular on account of the fame of  Brian Boru  (Gaelic <i>Brian Bóroimhe</i>) (  <i>c.</i> 940–1014 ), a warrior who was credited with driving the Vikings from Ireland and who eventually became high king of Ireland. In the Middle Ages it was relatively common in East Anglia, where it was introduced by Breton settlers, and in northern England, where it was introduced by Scandinavians from Ireland. It was quite popular in Yorkshire in the early 16th century, largely because it had long been a family name among the Stapletons, who had Irish connections. They first used it after  Sir Gilbert Stapleton  married  Agnes , the daughter of the great northern baron  Sir Brian fitzAlan . In Gaelic Scotland it was at first borne exclusively by members of certain professional families of Irish origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Bryan","meanings":["Variant of   Brian  , influenced by the usual spelling of the associated surname."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Bois","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from the Tartar nickname <i>Bogoris</i> ‘small’. Later, however, it was taken to be a shortened form of the Russian name <i>Borislav</i>, from <i>bor</i> ‘battle’ + <i>slav</i> ‘glory’. The name was borne in the 9th century by a ruler of Bulgaria who converted his kingdom to Christianity and gave shelter to disciples of saints  Cyril  and  Methodius  when they were expelled from Moravia. The name was also borne by a 10th-century Russian saint, son of  Prince Vladimir  of Kiev and brother of  St Gleb . It is as a result of his influence that <i>Boris</i> is one of the very few non-classical names that the Orthodox Church allows to be taken as a baptismal name (although the saint himself bore the baptismal name <i>Romanus</i>). It is borne by the British journalist and politician  Boris Johnson  (  b. 1964 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Brian de Bois Boice was born in 1290, in Essex, England, United Kingdom, his father, Gabriel de Bois Boice, was 26 and his mother, Mrs. Gabriel de Bois Boice, was 26. He had at least 1 son with Barton."},"et":{"1290–":"1290–Surnud","1290–Male":"1290–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1314–Male":"1314–Surnud","1265–Male":"1265–Surnud","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","1314":"1314","1265":"1265","1290":"1290","Theydon Garnon, Essex, England":"Theydon Garnon, Essex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1290–":"1290–Kuollut","1290–Male":"1290–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1314–Male":"1314–Kuollut","1265–Male":"1265–Kuollut","1265–Female":"1265–Kuollut","1314":"1314","1265":"1265","1290":"1290","Theydon Garnon, Essex, England":"Theydon Garnon, Essex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1290–":"1290–Décédé","1290–Male":"1290–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1314–Male":"1314–Décédé","1265–Male":"1265–Décédé","1265–Female":"1265–Décédée","1314":"1314","1265":"1265","1290":"1290","Theydon Garnon, Essex, England":"Theydon Garnon, Essex, Angleterre","Essex, England":"Essex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Brian de Bois Boice est né en 1290, à Essex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, Gabriel de Bois Boice, avait 26 ans et sa mère, Mrs. Gabriel de Bois Boice, avait 26 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Barton."},"de":{"1290–":"1290–Verstorben","1290–Male":"1290–Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1314–Male":"1314–Verstorben","1265–Male":"1265–Verstorben","1265–Female":"1265–Verstorben","1314":"1314","1265":"1265","1290":"1290","Theydon Garnon, Essex, England":"Theydon Garnon, Essex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Als Brian de Bois Boice 1290 in Essex, England, United Kingdom geboren wurde, war sein Vater Gabriel de Bois Boice 26 und seine Mutter Mrs. Gabriel de Bois Boice 26. Er hatte mit Barton mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"1290–":"1290–Desede","1290–Male":"1290–Desede","–Female":"Desede","1314–Male":"1314–Desede","1265–Male":"1265–Desede","1265–Female":"1265–Desede","1314":"1314","1265":"1265","1290":